#Calculate the tenure 
data$quit_date = as.Date(as.character(data$quit_date),format="%Y-%m-%d")
data$join_date  = as.Date(as.character(data$join_date),format="%Y-%m-%d")
data$tenure =round(as.numeric(data$quit_date-data$join_date)/365,2)
data$week = week(as.Date(data$quit_date,format="%Y-%m-%d"))
#Impute the quit result(0 or 1)
last_day = sapply("2015-12-13",FUN = as.Date,format="%Y-%m-%d")
data$quit = ifelse(data$`quit_date`>last_day|is.na(data$`quit_date`),0,1)

#Define the useful function for headcount
headcount <- function(id){
  df <- data[data$company_id==id&!is.na(data$join_date)&!is.na(data$quit_date),]
  dates <- unique(c(df$join_date,df$quit_date))
  head_count <- rep(0,length(dates))
  for(i in 1:length(dates)){
    head_count[i] = sum(df$join_date<dates[i],na.rm=TRUE)-sum(df$quit_date<dates[i],na.rm=TRUE)
  }
  df_return <- data.frame(company_id = rep(id,length(dates)), date=dates, headcount=head_count)
  df_return <- df_return[order(df_return$date),]
  return(df_return)
}
head_count_list <- lapply(sort(unique(data$company_id)), headcount)
head_count <- ldply(head_count_list, rbind)

Here, I want to impute the NAs in salary using K-nearest-neighbors

#Create dummy variables
dummy1 = dummy(data$company_id,sep=".")
dummy2 = dummy(data$dept,sep=".")
data  = data.frame(data[3:7],dummy1,dummy2)
#Impute NAs in "salary"
index_na = which(is.na(data$salary))
train <- data[!is.na(data$salary),]
test <- data[is.na(data$salary),]
knn <- knn.reg(train=as.matrix(train[-c(2:4)]),test=test[-c(2:4)], y=train$salary,k=8,algorithm="kd_tree")
data$salary[index_na] = knn$pred
#Impute NAs in "tenure"
index_na2 = which(is.na(data$tenure))
train <- data[!is.na(data$tenure),]
test <- data[is.na(data$tenure),]
knn2 <- knn.reg(train=as.matrix(train[-c(3:4)]),test=test[-c(3:4)], y=train$tenure,k=8,algorithm="kd_tree")

Task 2 - Main factors that drive employee churn.

The top three important factors are “tenure”, “salary” and “seniority” ; The employees with lower or mid “salary” are more likely to quit their job, as they may want to seek for jobs with better pay, while employees with higher salary are always satisfied with their pay. Employees with lower “tenure” are also likely to quit their job, as many employees may quit thier job in probation period, where they find the job not suitable for them or they may just want to gather some experience and then seek for a better opportunity.

—-Promotion(0 or 1), which is cheap to get from HR tracking system; —-Projects finished during the tenure, which is cheap to get from HR tracking system; —-Percent of salary increased —-Personal Assessment of the company —-Company bonus information
